<dl id="n03010d"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n03" href="#n03010d">N03 (VI.B.3)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n03all.htm#n03010d"> 10(d)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> coppersmith bishop <small>Blue</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n03010d"><li>FW 228.05 </li><li><a href="../../flex/kb/lexkb.htm#n03010d">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/kb/l39kb.htm#n03010d">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n03010d">MS missing</ms> </li><li>JJA not reproduced <a name="kad4" href="../../FF/fdra/kda.htm#kbd2">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/kb/kbd2.htm#n03010d">Draft: II.1&sect;2.2</a> </li> </ul><mm class="note">Note: Entered by <a name="sh1007n" href="sh1all.htm#sh1007n">Sheet i-7(n)</a> </mm> <blockquote class="sources">The position which the artist and the craftsman held in society is an indication of how the arts were loved and esteemed in Ireland. The title of scribe is frequently used in our ancient literature to enhance the dignity of a bishop, and we find that St. Conlaeth, the first Bishop of Kildare, was a skilled worker in metals. St. Dega was also a celebrated artificer and scribe; one of St. Patrick&apos;s three smiths was Fortchern, son of Laery, King of Ireland, and it is stated in the Tripartite Life that the holy <mark>Bishop Assicus was his coppersmith</mark>. <small> J.M. Flood, <a name="JMFI" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#JMFI"><cite title="source">Ireland: Its Saints and Scholars</cite></a> (n.d) 106</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
